From Ann
Elynia, Loraine Co. Ohio, June 5th 1862
My Dear Sisters ( to Betsy Conant)

             I have had it in my mind to write to you every day this long time But one thing & another steals away the time I often think of you & Esther & do so want to know not only your external condition & circumstances, but what you think and feel your joys, & Sorrows, your comfort & your trials-
             Can you realise what aged people we are I frequently set myself to ponder the subject and try to feel ____ but I cannot - that I am as old as people of my age us'd to be when I was young persons as old as my children are were very old folks then
             I can see when I look in the glass how wrinkled I am & can see how Mis Sim' Steams look'd to me when I went there once, when I was a child, with her mouth all "caved in" it didn't occur to me that I should ever look so
            Perhaps you will laugh at me when I tell you that I have lately got a set of false teeth my children have teased me to - this ten years but I had one tooth remaining & could not feel willing to till a few weeks since that one left me --- & Anna's husband & Isaac persuaded me to have some false ones
            I can eat with them & they have not occasion'd me any pain      My health is very good & I have every privelege & every comfort that I can need and I surely ought to be very thankful I do feel that I am very underserving that I have done very little good in the world to what I might have done & ought to have done
Completed

I wish you could be here & see the abundance of Fruit all ours this part of the country - Isaac has on his lot of 5 or 6 acres besides Apple trees - about 80 peach - 40 pear - & 25 or 30 cherry trees full as they can hold of fruit - much the greatest part, set out within 5 years he has some dwarf pear trees not more than 3 or so feet high full of pears down to within 6 or 7 inches of the ground He delights in his orchard & garden & loads it with manure of every kind. 

      Isaac & his family are well they have had six children ---- have buried 3 ---- prospect of another this Summer    Annna & her folks are well she has been without a hir'd girl about a year - to learn her girls to work about house which they were not very likely to do if they kept a girl all the time
      A Soldier return'd here yesterday who has been a prisoner in Rebeldom almost a year their prisoners have suffer'd dreadfully ______while these taken by our side have been treated with all kindness - some of them officers at Columbus were allow'd for a while to retain their black waiters! Charles's wife has two Brothers in the Army one of them Summer Rettcedge a Luit. in the 2 Marine Regiment has been a prisoner more than a year Charles's oldest boy is here yet attending School is a very good boy - is very much like his Father           I wish you would tell me something about Joanna & whether she ever rec'd a letter I sent her some months ago
        Tell Esther she must take this as written to her too & write to me________ & I wish you would tell me whether Brother Williams upholds slavery & slave - holders yet ___ I have more folks to write to than either of you so you must not wait for me but both write soon to your affectionate Sister A. M. N.
Completed

Milo Aug. 28 1839

Dear Sister, 

               As I have not written any unclear thing? to you Since you went away which can be called a letter I will begin at the beginning. I was sorry that I was up in the potato field when you went away so that I could not say goodbye. I started to come down but found it was too late. I am glad that you had such a good journey, and get along so finely there. The "posy patch" prospers finely.
                The heap by the unclear is covered with Ari - colored violets & looketh pretty. The columbine (purple) looked pretty & is sprouting up from the root so as to look pretty next year The foxglove was very profusely covered with flowers & looked very pretty. The Mullein pink mother says is very splendid. It really is, & has been and will be for some time to come. The flowers are purple. It looketh very pretty. The two pink roots from Mr. Hoxie's flower profusely & looketh pretty. There is some large double red sweet smelling poppies, and some small Double & bright red poppies very curis leaves etc. which looketh pretty. African Hibiscus & sweet peas blue bells catchfly, candy - tufts marigolds chrysanthemums white & red single poppies as usual.

Our plaquey great new yelloy marigolds are just beginning to flow. We have abundance of White morning glories which looketh pretty & some blue & purple but no red ones. The kittens have grown greatly. and are very pretty.
Completed

I suppose you know how we had a tame fox?  We have got a tame muskrat what summeth about the house & is about as tame as a kitten, cats milk, parsnips roots, leaves of turnip cabbage beet & bean & pea pods & most everything else.  His castle is in the closet west of the chimney whence he can sully out to the kitchen or pasture.  He hath dug him a hole one entrance being in the closet & the other behind the backroom chimney.  He is the pet, as cleanly as a kitten & not so mischievous.  Meow being called mukky-mukkee,-mukky-he cometh.  We caught a young wild cuck & kept it a spell but it would not grow tame & we let it go.  One day Saul & I went up to Booby Brook fishing & caught 5 great pickerel, 2 eels & duck & one mussquash??.  We have got about  haying.  Charles has got a cradle & cradled acres of wheat & 1 acre of oats.
Ann got home last Friday night so in a very good plight.  Only she left 2 of Isaac's books & Mrs Bush's letter tools & ((unclear)) behind-((unclear)) came the twenty sixth of July one weeke before the vacation commenced, & is going back the last of this week I suppose.  He is going back to the same place as (Ms. Malkiss) which is a very good place I guess.  He & James F. Walker have corresponded during the vacation. J.F.W is a brother of Ms. Asa Walker about 20 years old I believe, studying law.
Eliiab was intending to write some in his letter but he cut his hand today pretty bad so  that he cannot.
Completed

I must not write much longer for I have got to write a letter to C.C Barnes and send with this by Mr Wells, who goes I believe by next Friday.  Ellen Lee has been very sick but is better now so that she rides out some.  I wants thee, to write to me, a great long letter pretty quick.  It is 9 o'clock.  I must go to bed.  I shall be sleeping in the morning.  I am afraid.  Good Bye
L Lucy. M Metcalfe


                                                                                                                                                                      Joseph M.Metcalf

To my Dear Daughter
We have an opportunity to send letters by Mr Wells but Alas!  I have no time hardly to write as I ((unclear)) for Isaac away he has but 2 days more to stay at home this time and I have got a ((unclear)) to make an other little matters.
29th Eve.  I guess you don't know nothin about our fox, so one day I was coming home from ((unclear)) when I saw a young fox in the road and I run after him and I caught him & I lugged him home and we dug him a hole out between here & the "posey patch" & he lived a& growed prettily and got very tame but 1 day he died and we took off his hide.
From yours affectionate Father.  Joseph M Metcalf.  Good bye.
I have not much time or room to write now but will just say how you'll have a ((unclear)) time to work & study and read & don't forget my Dear Daughter to spend part of every day in earnest prayer and I do become full and not let too much time slip away while you stand talking with your neighbours [Ms J.L Marion] it will perhaps be more than jus.t I have some fear that you will feel lonesome but you new and if you are well occupied take good care of your health so as to be well and strong and not let Almeda have anythings hard to do as she must be very careful or them always be an invalid.   If you rise very early and  ((unclear)) you can do a good deal of work and get time to improve your mind too-Don't get too much engaged about one  thing to the neglect of others.  Be a good girl & shall write a good long letters by and by.
Completed

Dear Lucy
I suppose P & A are gone so you will get all the letters this time.  I found the boat very crowded, and the sleeping accommodations so poor that I chose to stay on deck as long as there was any lady to stay with me but at last I went down into the cabin and succeeded in finding a place to lay my head though without any pillow:  I slept pretty well, however and rose early enough to see the entrance into Portland, but soon I had to go below again with the sick headache;  I was not sick; Indeed the sea was so very calm that hardly any one was sick.  I had rather a dull day of it being obliged to lie down most all of the time till evening, but then we had a very pleasant time it was bright moonlight and the passage from Bucksport to Bangor you know is interesting.  I found C waiting for me and without stopping we rode out to Moses by moonlight, arrived there at ten o'clock, found them all abed.  Started next morning at six arrived home about noon.  Found the folks well, but wondering greatly at the delay of a ((unclear)) in our coming.  Mothers health is quite good now:  little Olive helps a great deal, I verily believe she does more work than you do.  She is very good natured & tries to please.  Your posy patch seeds my very highest expectations.  I have gathered a nosegay almost every day of about twenty different kinds-under the window are the scarlet bean and sweet pea, and the two gorgeous marigold and chrysanthemums and several others one in full bloom.  Charles is very busy about his harvesting & the boys have to work very hard.  Eliab cut his hand pretty badly yesterday.  Ann's geranium is alive but it got ((unclear)) shaking the unclear when we had left
Mother & Ann Sept. 1899
Completed

I went to Sebe to meeting last sabbath, heard Mr Batchelder preach a good sermon. I stopped at the Sabbath school saw about 30 scholars and 5 teachers; quite a contrast to our sabbath school. I am very sorry about Isaac's books and Mr Bush's letters. as soon as James comes home, he must send them in a package to be left at the office in Bangor: it is a pity that James must be at so much trouble about them when they might so easily have been brought but the greatest pity is, that Isaac will be obliged to do without his books for two or three weeks when he really needs them. I have written to Miss Samson by Mr Wells and I want you should ask her whether she has received it and let me know in your next letter. There is always an uncertainty about letters when sent by private conveyance therefore I want you should inquire about it. There is a book that I borrowed of Lydia Lawson, which I wish you would call there and return. Martha and Ellen rode down to see me Monday morning just as we were going to washing but did not get out of the chaise because Ellen was not able to bear the fatique of getting out and in. Mrs. Hile came along yesterday for mother to go to Mrs. Henry Largent's s visiting' but when they got to the river they found her gone away, so Mrs Hill spent the afternoon here. Abby is at home and Naomi is not very well. I have scratched down all the news I can think of so good bye
Love to Mr. T and little B.           E.A.
Completed

Joseph & I have just sent a little letter to Joseph Hill lo carry to you and since then have read: The hymn Book and what shall I call it? not a handsome letter but better than nothing I'm sorry for your Lucy distress about unclear but it is of very little consiquence--- not knowing the circumstances I am no judge of the case but I should think that the dress for the party too unclear of very little consequences where there is so many no one is seen you know ------- I say to you Ann & Lucy that I don't feel exactly willing that I don't feel exactly willing that L should stay at Mr. butler while Mrs etc are gone without some one else there I dont know any thing but what Mr C is worthy of the utmost conficence but I feel that I should rather she would not & that it is not quite proper but do as you think best I long to have you get home as soon as you ascertain what day your school closes let us know we shall need a great double sleigh to fetch you all three home C. is here now is going back tomorrow morning O he wants you should send or unclear by Mr. Joseph Hill I will send the case and a little pence of money good bye
Completed

Joseph seems to enjoy exceedingly, likewise we all, the prospect of your getting smart and coming home to stay while Samll is gone into the woods.  He says that as to accommodations they shall be plenty for if needed he can sleep out in the piazza or under the shed that she may have his sleeping room or any way if she can but come.   Partridge, like other cold meats are said to be much better for invalids.  I should think it would do for you to begin to take a little broth ((unclear))
I'm following your directions in regard to advising Almeda about fixing up bc I did in my Blundering Inadvertent way so speak as to offend or rather grieve but I'm sure I did not mean it in the ((unclear)) takes more than you mean you know.  She feels that you & perhaps I have too much thought about fashion stores.  It is true that in the world we shall have tribulation and that the more we live above and regardless of the world & place our hurt & happiness in Christ where only his peace is found the better it is for us, we are apt to seek worldly gratification & think we have it when it fairly analyzed we would find a considerable mixture of something else.
I think a little season spent here with Joseph would be not only pleasant but ((unclear)) to both you and Lucy.  Lucy must get well fast and come home & what a fun time we will have here in Josephs lazy warm room.
Completed

Arrived home in safety before it was quite as dark as Egyptian darkness it began to grow dark the fog was so very thick soon after we left Bradford  from a Mrs Blander or something about the  Ostler we were detained longer than John intended.  My back did ache before I got there, but got nicely rested.  Felt considerable apprehension about getting home in safety on account of the darkness, but we got along nicely & all was well.  There was no men striking  appearance of displeasure on the ((unclear)) of Joseph  or any of the rest but they all with one accord began to say they were sorry to see me and "kinder" scold me for not staying longer with you, that they could do without me just as well as not, i.e as they, better than, you could so that the danger seems to be that ((unclear)) not be wanted nowhere no now.  I do want to know how you are this very day & how you are every day.  If you are really getting strong-gaining in health & strength everyday.  I should think that in a few days after Almeda gets there you could dismiss your Nurse & thereby get along with less expense and more satisfaction.  Almeda is very kind hearted and capable, only like me she is apt to be a little negligent and forgetful-------If you see Eliah tell him not to get some paper to make some envelope as Joseph requested some time ago and not to get at present Harpers new Monthly Magazine but give no more than 20 cents a number Isaac says that is the price.
J.M to every lady----if to be found in your ((unclear)) and you can bring em conveniently & spare em as well as most should desire you, to visit:  Amm to bring Telemanque, la Henriade , in  ((unclear)) testament, "Scotts pratical work of the last Minstrel" Greenleafs arithmetic, if you have it, key it to Emersons second post, 1/2 quine or one ((unclear)) of envelope paper white would not be preferred unless equally as cheap, each of these commissions, to be deferred or omitted if more convenient 2 packages were presented to me for which not having ((unclear)) uase & transmit one to you
Completed

Mother  Hampden
30 May 1850

                                                                                                     Hampden 30th May 1850

My Dear Children
I will just speak a word or two to tell you that I arrived safely before dark-rather rough, muddy travelling but I was not very indeed tird found Lucy-getting better she ways-but she is rather slim.  She rode out a little way today tho' she cannot sit up more than an hour at a time she has been very sick-but begin to have a little appetite now-she thinks she shall soon be considerably better-she probably took cold and she has worked too hard & I don't believe  she will be so well as she was before for some time-Sam'l got a skien of black worsted for card & four tassels for the pall cloth-at 1/apiece the skien, 10 cents I don't think it will take near all the worsted if there is enough left  to ((unclear)) for the change I'll take it-if they wish.
I hope you will all of you, encourage and assist Mr Temple in his Labour of Love----I do advise & labor & thrive with J Dolero he must be car'd for---prayed for and ((unclear)) in his ((unclear)) cause.  How much good he may do in the world if now he should turn and set out in a right course.
I'm afraid you wont all be faithful about getting pay for preaching---Sam'll will speak to Mr Cutts about carrying cheap-think he will for a
Completed

dollar a trip______________
I wish you would have Lucy come down and clear up Josephs room  here so that Albina need not have too much to do ___________& do you Isaac it is up and fix the straw in Josephs bed-because of my sore finger I didn't do anything to it for some time-I shall be thinking about you all-take good care of Jose-and Charlie-and be good all of you.
My love to Mr Temple tell him he of good courage God WILL prosper his work.
Lucy says, she began to get better as soon as she saw me coming-take care and write to me every da.
Lucy says tell Mr. Temple we would be pleased to have him call here to put a pleasant walk Mrs Well said he is coming down some time with some of the students.
Sam'l is just going, I can't write any more.  Goodbye
H M Metcalfe
Completed

Hampden June 10

My Dear Children
I write a little to let you know, & because I want to know, whether I ought to  go/come home.  L is better rode up to Bangor last week and then was not so well-went to meeting in the forenoon Sunday.  Monday was not able to sit up an hour-she seems a little better every other day-don't appear to have any fever hardly now is I think on the whole convalescent and wants to go to Milo to see you all very much, will as soon as next week I think if she is able.  Till she is considerably better she will need me or somebody here-now I want you should all tell me what I ought to do-I don't feel just right to be away from J so long-(not that I do him any good when I am there as Isaac does every thing) and I fear that Allina has too much to do to take care of so many all you lot of boys & Mr Temple-I think your couple of hours for dear Isaac might be very acceptable to her-have you set up a bed in the east chamber or anywhere  Lucy has given me some stuff for Charley  a dress so Allena better not get any till will come-tell Almeda make up Lucy's dress but not fix her bonnet till we come if she has not-Lucy you know is good for talking how every thing should be done if she is half sick-does Almeda want & should get a
Completed

shoes for Lucy.  Samuel has spoke with Mr Cutts about carrying up the students.  He will carry for a dollar a trip (he said he'd give 2 or 3 dollars besides.) S will pay part of it I guess.  I am going to bring up Lucys ((unclear)) for Allina to look at before she makes hers, better ((unclear)) colour than old dress.  Great rain yesterday I'm 'fraid the ((unclear)) is all flood again, write some tell me how you all get along-take care of Josie & of Charlie.
If Lucy can only get well enough she & I will come up with cab ourself alone (leave Jane to keep house) but I fear she wont she is so unwell yesterday & today-but perhaps she'll be better tomorrow in haste A.M.M
I myself, Lucy, am at present this afternoon feeling better than I did, without hardly knowing why, except that Jane bought me some beautiful young checkerberry leaves, which I have munched with much gusto.  Mother and I are having a nice time.  I feel sort of selfish and guilty to keep  her here away from Josie so long, but I don't want her to go till I get well enough to go with her, which I hope will be soon.  Samuel is about concluding to go into the Mill (as ((unclear)) is very anxious to have him, and the prospect of an appointment as surveyor is slight this year) for $40.00 per month, until it starts by might, and after that at the old wages.  JAne goes to school, has some new books, gets her lessons well, and ((unclear)) tries to do her best in school, but is the same noisey fly away thing as ever not at school.  Though she helps nicely out of school-Almeda must not flatter herself about a dress for Charlie-it is only
Completed

part of an old dark gingham dress of mine which mother said would answer for her, and the rest of which I am making up for Jane.  I want to come to Milo dreadfully.  Think I should go into summer quarters there with the rest of you, if I had not a husband and Jane to look after.  How I shall set you to making "horse stable carpets" when I come, Albina.  They are handsome.  Mother forgot to bring her parasol and desires some of you to make a suitable measurement of the quantity of silk needs any to cover it, and communicate the same soon.  Mother wishes after a suitable and sufficient inspection of the rug carpet, you would send your opinions individually and collectively as to the propriety and expediency of getting a new one.  I am lolling on the bed-The doors are open into the dining room, where "Pa and Ma" and Jane are eating supper.  They'll fix me up a ((unclear)) of coarse bread and slops suppose, by and by-yah.  They treat me pretty well though considerin.  Tell Almeda to hurry and get Lucy's dress done before I come, and we'll conclude about the rest of her clothes.  
Samuel says tell Joseph Hitcher is defaulted-Thurston is in the way-continued for judgement. Thurston hopes to get a chance to go west and go into the coal trade.  Brandy wine is being sheathed.  Senator being stood could not be done when the other repairs were made last spring, water was so high.  Henry Brown has lately come into possession of a new son.  Samuel is 'bout ready to go-do write a great deal-for Mothers sake if you don't for mine.  Good night.
Lucy
Completed

Thursday Nov 22nd 9 1/2 evening

My Dear Daughter
I have just received your kind letter I wrote a little to you in the same with a bit of a letter to Ethel about the 14th or 15th which perhaps you have not received-I thank you very much for your letters and for your invitation to visit &c--------I really want to see you in your fine house am glad you like it so well.  I hope your health will be good and you will have nothing to hinder your enjoying much happiness therein.
You ask when I will visit you I think I had better not yet a while you will probably for   (unclear)) time  nowadays, had a good deal of company and we shall both enjoy it getter if I wait till midwinter or so or certainly till after Isaac comes home-I have had letters from him since this month came in (he a good boy isn't he) I think he will when Joseph gets ready to come home come and wait upon him home and then I can go to Hampden when he goes along back.  
Almedas foot is better so that we can go about  to see her neighbours on crutches & about ((unclear)) them.  She went twice to Grafton ((unclear)) today, their child is very sick____I almost think hard of Joseph  ((unclear)) disappointed 2 or 3 lost mails, he has not written to me only once since he went away.  I feel very anxious about him .  I want to know how long he means to stay & whether is getting better___I don't think Jane could mend that cloak he had last winter.  It's too much solid and too small.  I can fix her warm enough I guess unless it is very much colder Saturday than it is today-I hardly know whether to send Janes old hood.  I am thinking that I can ((unclear)) the two and rip and colour them and mark me one that ((unclear)) you know is pretty good but if you can make use of it for her I will send it.

 I expect I can sell my wool here out anyways for 27 cents a pound and shall have many enough to get a cloak.  Jo don't trouble yourself any more you are good kind daughter to think so much about me when you have so much to do-I guess I can fix my Mum  over  well enough, think I can.
Completed

you tell of being abed apart of the forenoon, have you not been as well as normal________I haven't anything very special you know to keep me in one place more than another so if any of you are not well at any time and I can be useful to you I can start my  stumps in a that time if you but let me know but if all are well____it seems to me I had better be here at present but I shall probably write again soon____shall have a letter from Joseph tomorrow I guess___Do you write again soon & tell us how whether you ((unclear)) "safe and sound".
Angella Everett has got a son so has Mrs Hicken & Mrs M.((unclear)) & I don't know how many more___Mrs Hicken has  gone on the river to work the ((unclear)) before her babe was a fortnight old-they have absolutely nothing to eat except what C ((unclear)) they have had about all his wages now and he doesn't again to pay him any till winter they will not move away from Almeda this winter & I don't see hardly how they are going to live till next fall to say nothing about building a house. 
23rd I am some afraid from what  Isaac wrote in his last letter that he will not come any further than Waterford if Joseph does not come home but I shall feel very sadly about it if he does not-Joseph I suppose will think he had better not-If I don't have a letter from Joseph today what shall I do
Allena has cut and made a vest for Charlie, out of his old blue coat all only I am making the button hole .  Charlie sits on the floor before me making a cat home has got it as cats high in regular order his cats have rolld under the stove so he goes round to the wood box and gets a stick to poke them and without asking any help he is a persevering little fellow.  I am about getting my carpet now or rather a part of it.  I want Ehab to get me 3 or 4 pounds of Cotton twine such as weavers use for loomers at Mrs Bughees or I can't get all my rags  none have sent what ((unclear)) I have got to Mrs ((unclear)) to weave shall make another piece if I get some more ((unclear)) I don't believe you can read this, I wish I had some ink.
Completed

Saturday

Charles was intending to go to Bangor the day we came up or the next day but for the death of Mr. Sargents little boy, he could not of course _____ But assist & sympathise they seem to feel this was very much.  Mr S says he had buried a Brother & Father & Mother but never felt grief like this.
I brought away thinking if Josephs one of Isaac shirts  an old one but perhaps he would mean it some more so I'll it back.  I don't think it best to get very coarse cloth for Josephs shirts.  I should think such as you get for Sam'l if I want you should get about 5 yds for me also.
I wish you would write to Ann soon I suspect the Mr & Mrs Hopkiss she is with are very uncomfortable folks to live with and are mean.  I think that she does not & can not enjoy herself there______ you know Josephs stern philosophy he wrote to her that she had better not come home ________ but I feel bad to have her so situated.  She is very apt to enjoy herself wherever she is comfortably situated ________ It is hard to be a strong away from all ones friends _______ I wish she would come home and stay and be happy____ Joseph takes his ((unclear)) sheet in the morning  ias as well as he was, he was no more fatigued than I expected - he sleeps in the large bedroom__________ I am afraid that with all his philosophy he will be unable to keep up his spirit in the long days so monotonous so little to excite or pleasantly interest - however he's getting ahead right  ((unclear)) I tell him he has just  walked across the room, alone except this comes where before he left W. he used to go walk with 2 canes 3 times the length of the Piazza & repeat 1 operation several times  ((unclear))
Completed

Dear Daughter how did you get home why haven't you let us know, & whether you found Sam'l alive and well, and whether he was glad to see you I've a lot of things I want to say to you that I ought to have said when you were here but forgot besides a great many that have occur'd to me since but I cant think of any thing that is just right to say now, or cant think of it, I'm so confus'd with finishing off four other letters for Jess and me
C. handed you 3,00 with which I believe they want you to get 20 yds, 4 cloth, 6" good for shirts with linen (4 or 5' yds)- skein unbleach'd threat & shirt buttons, also Table Cloth & crash if convenient for you to get them and if it was not to much plaque Eliab so when he has so much to see to I should vent? you to get some a little money which will be to C's Albinas credit for eggs and get a 1/2 doz knives & forks she needs 'em but no matter you all have enough else to do or ought to have
ya want 10 yds of the 4 cent Cotton Cloth so you had better get a whole piece 
Do write after I want to know how you get along everyday
Completed

Mother July
13th July 1850
My Dear Daughter we receiv'd your letter & kerchief by Mr Furber today- John looks very thin am fraid he studied to hard but perhaps work will fat him up again
I am sorry Isaac has got to hurry away so that he cant stop, any  with you_ I hardly know how we shall get along with out him_ Joseph has now got a bad Cold and Cough what shall I do for him_ believe I shall try Thoroughmert? Candy
How I should have deceas'd if I had been with you when you were eating your Beef- very cheap food & very good 
I wish I could have heard Mr. Temples account of Milo if he calls to see you give my love to him_ he is a very good Man very much indeed devoted to the cause of Christ I think he has already been the means of accomplishing great good in Town_ Mr Sargent (uncle Henry) says there is no other man that would do as much good to come here & preach now as he would_ we don't consider our? turnips? hardly eatable now but will send if he can carry conveniently_ we ar very worry about your visit we did not diskiver it til after Lucy was gone 
Our Peas in blossom a week ago do to eat in a week or so I guess raspberries dont begin to be ripe- you smut try to find something more important to think about than eating I hope you dont spice your mince pies too much & unclear that you dont eat too much of them- they'll be quite a unclear at this time of year but wont keep long will they I wish I had one- we expect to have Alfred Jaden? Dolem Boabar & Welch boy here this week Joseph and all of us rather think now that it would be better for Charles to take care of Joseph and have more help on the farm he could get at any
Completed

one may often staying for he could have to do nearly half as much work as he does now I hope Eliab can come home when he leaves tomorn and spend the winter he never would regret it I think it would be such a comfort to Joseph but he says that Eliab mind not that he ought to be in better business if he dont go to work somewhere that he ought to go off to Cuba, N. Orleans on somewhere and learn something I doubt whether Alfred can be contented here long
I guess you'll just ride up here and stay a week or so in the first part of August shan't you now think of it & I guess you'll think you will_ Isaac has just been out and brought in some Peas big enough to eat they were sow'd in the 1st of june I would send you a teacupfull only I suppose they are plenty enough in the market_ Joseph says if you have a right gave a chance send Smellees Phylosephy of Naturat History and a good specimen of Sweet Briar- in your Book you have a specimen of Rosa Lucida mark'd R. rubiginosa, which is sweet briar such you have in your garden, therefore preserve specimen to take place under your label, we will inset, lucida, perhaps milida.
Joseph says dont be in a hurry about your Book but fix it up nice not have it homogenious mess
now forget to come home- tell Mr. Temple there was a large Pills? Class last Sabbath a wish they could have had a better Teacher than I think Mr. Shont? is- the largest number of S. S. So Joseph says I must write and explain the mushment - He has got mush enough for two breakfasts & meal enough for 2 or 3 days so if you are not coming as soon as Wednesday or Friday at farthest - he want you send meal and mush stuff by stage soon (& be sure that you bring up  the letter Isaac has just written to you) We kept looking for you all days last week.
